           #:message{:content
                     "Our plate glass production process involves several key steps:\n\n1. <b>Batching</b>: Raw materials (silica sand, soda ash, limestone, and cullet) are carefully measured and mixed. This mixture is then melted in a furnace.\n\n2. <b>Melting</b>: The batch is melted in a furnace at temperatures around 1700°C to form molten glass. This process can take several hours.\n\n3. <b>Floating</b>: The molten glass is then poured onto a bath of molten tin in a float chamber. Here, the glass spreads out and forms a flat surface. The thickness of the glass is controlled by the speed at which the glass ribbon is pulled from the chamber.\n\n4. <b>Annealing (Cooling)</b>: After forming, the glass ribbon moves through an annealing lehr, where it is gradually cooled. This controlled cooling process relieves internal stresses.\n\n5. <b>Inspection and Cutting</b>: The glass is then inspected for quality. Once approved, it is cut into panels as per the order specifications.\n\n6. <b>Packaging</b>: Finally, the glass panels are packed and prepared for shipping to customers.\n\nThroughout this process, quality control is a critical component, ensuring the final product meets our high standards and customer specifications. Efficiency and scheduling are crucial to manage due to the continuous flow and high energy costs associated with production.",
                     :from :surrogate,
                     :id 6,
                     :tags [:process-description],
                     :time #inst "2024-05-09T20:26:27.626-00:00"}
